===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `sed` yek dastoor ghavi baraye dastkari va tagheer matn dar file-ha ast. Ba `sed` mitoonid joosteju konid, jaigozin konid, hazf konid, ya ezafe konid kalamat va khat-ha ra.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `sed 's/old/new/g' file.txt`  --> 🔄 Jaigozini hameye "old" ba "new" dar file.txt
    🔹 `sed -i 's/old/new/g' file.txt` --> 💾 Tagheer mostaghim dar file.txt
    🔹 `sed '/pattern/d' file.txt` --> 🗑 Hazf khat-hayi ke "pattern" dar anha vojood darad.
    🔹 `sed -n '2p' file.txt` --> 🔢 Chap khat dovom az file.txt.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ sed 's/apple/orange/g' fruits.txt

    🔹 Jaigozini hameye kalame "apple" ba "orange" dar file `fruits.txt` va chap natije dar terminal.

    $ sed -i 's/red/blue/g' colors.txt

    🔹 Jaigozini hameye kalame "red" ba "blue" dar file `colors.txt` va zakhire tagheerat dar hamin file.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ sed 's/cat/dog/g' pet.txt

    🔹 Agar `pet.txt` shamel "The cat is sleeping" bashad, natije chap shode "The dog is sleeping" khahad bood.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `sed` command is a powerful stream editor used for manipulating text in files.  With `sed`, you can search, replace, delete, or insert words and lines.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `sed 's/old/new/g' file.txt`  --> 🔄 Replace all occurrences of "old" with "new" in file.txt
    🔹 `sed -i 's/old/new/g' file.txt` --> 💾 Directly modify the file.txt
    🔹 `sed '/pattern/d' file.txt` --> 🗑 Delete lines containing "pattern".
    🔹 `sed -n '2p' file.txt` --> 🔢 Print the second line from file.txt.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ sed 's/apple/orange/g' fruits.txt

    🔹 Replaces all occurrences of the word "apple" with "orange" in the file `fruits.txt` and prints the result to the terminal.

    $ sed -i 's/red/blue/g' colors.txt

    🔹 Replaces all occurrences of the word "red" with "blue" in the file `colors.txt` and saves the changes directly to the file.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ sed 's/cat/dog/g' pet.txt

    🔹 If `pet.txt` contains "The cat is sleeping", the printed result will be "The dog is sleeping".